<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-270-844  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 270 844.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 15 1989 v23 n20 p104(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Welcome to Unix training: the flexibility of Unix frees users butdemands a lot from trainers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Swartz, Ray.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The programming environment of the Unix system presents a uniquechallenge to corporate trainers.andP;  The system requires trainers toknow much more about the topics covered in each class thantraining in DOS, for example, because Unix's flexibility lets itbe used in several ways.andP;  Unix's features and capabilities can beused directly as part of applications or as development tools.andO;The difference between Unix and other environments results fromthe system's command processors - the Bourne, C and Korn shells -and from its unusual commands that are useful both individuallyand in combinations.andP;  Trainers must be able to teach the sameconcepts in different ways, depending on the students and theirlevel of technical knowledge.andP;  Steps involved in creating acorporate Unix environment include assessing the current level ofUnix capability and determining the level of training required.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     User TrainingUNIXProgrammersGuidelines.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>